---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="Framework" description="The AI Matrix framework: access, agency, and the four quadrants of global AI adoption.">
  <section class="container page-content">
    <div class="prose">
      <h1>The AI Matrix Framework</h1>

      <p class="lede">
        The AI Matrix plots countries on two axes: how broadly AI reaches their
        population (access) and how productively people use it once it arrives
        (agency). The framework comes from
        <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18181372" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Simpson (2026)</a>
        and is recomputed here each time Anthropic publishes new data.
      </p>

      <h2>Two dimensions</h2>

      <h3>Access: how many people use AI</h3>
      <p>
        Access is the log-transformed per-capita rate of conversations with
        Claude. A high-access country has AI reaching a broad share of its
        population. A low-access country has usage concentrated among a few.
      </p>

      <h3>Agency: what they do with it</h3>
      <p>
        Agency is a composite of four indicators: how often people co-create
        with AI (task iteration, learning, validation) rather than just issuing
        directives, how often tasks succeed, and the education level reflected
        in prompts. High agency means people treat AI as a collaborator. Low
        agency means they treat it as a vending machine.
      </p>

      <h2>Four quadrants</h2>

      <div class="quadrant-grid">
        <div class="quadrant quadrant--elite-empowerment">
          <h3><span class="stage-badge stage-badge--elite-empowerment">Elite Empowerment</span></h3>
          <p>Low access, high agency. Few people have AI, but those who do use it for real work. India, Brazil, and South Africa sit here.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="quadrant quadrant--full-empowerment">
          <h3><span class="stage-badge stage-badge--full-empowerment">Full Empowerment</span></h3>
          <p>High access, high agency. AI is widely available and people co-create with it. No country sits here yet.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="quadrant quadrant--full-dependency">
          <h3><span class="stage-badge stage-badge--full-dependency">Full Dependency</span></h3>
          <p>Low access, low agency. AI barely reaches the population, and what use exists skews toward coursework. Kenya and much of Sub-Saharan Africa sit here.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="quadrant quadrant--passive-dependency">
          <h3><span class="stage-badge stage-badge--passive-dependency">Passive Dependency</span></h3>
          <p>High access, low agency. Lots of people have AI, but they mostly issue one-off commands or use it for personal tasks. The US, UK, Germany, and Japan sit here.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>Why it matters</h2>
      <p>
        Most talk about the "AI divide" stops at access: who has AI and who
        doesn't. That's half the picture. The US has high access but middling
        agency. India has low access but its users co-create at high rates.
        Policy that only measures adoption misses what happens after adoption.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="/methodology">Full methodology &rarr;</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .page-content {
    padding: var(--space-lg) 0;
    max-width: var(--max-width-prose);
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .lede {
    font-size: var(--text-h3);
    color: var(--text-primary);
    line-height: 1.5;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-lg);
  }

  .quadrant-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-md);
    margin: var(--space-md) 0 var(--space-lg);
  }

  .quadrant {
    padding: var(--space-md);
    background: var(--bg-surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 8px;
  }

  .quadrant h3 {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-xs);
  }

  .quadrant p {
    font-size: var(--text-small);
  }

  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .quadrant-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
